"Vaquer-Sunyer R., Duarte C.M.","Temperature effects on oxygen thresholds for hypoxia in marine benthic organisms",2011,"Global Change Biology","17","5",,"1788","1797",,,10.1111/j.1365-2486.2010.02343.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79953273129&partnerID=40&md5=1b6c4011785039adede588223dd8058c","Department of Global Change Research, IMEDEA, CSIC-UIB, C/Miquel Marqués 21, 07190 Esporles (Mallorca), Spain","Vaquer-Sunyer, R., Department of Global Change Research, IMEDEA, CSIC-UIB, C/Miquel Marqués 21, 07190 Esporles (Mallorca), Spain; Duarte, C.M., Department of Global Change Research, IMEDEA, CSIC-UIB, C/Miquel Marqués 21, 07190 Esporles (Mallorca), Spain","The effect of warming on the oxygen requirements and the survival of benthic organisms under hypoxia was tested using a meta-analysis of published results of experiments evaluating the effects of temperature on the median lethal time and median lethal concentration of benthic macrofauna under hypoxia. The meta-analysis confirmed that survival times under hypoxia were reduced by on average 74% and that median lethal concentration increased by on average 16% when marine benthic organisms were exposed to warmer temperatures. Warming reduced survival times of marine benthic macrofauna under hypoxia by a median of 3.95±1.67h°C-1 and increased the oxygen thresholds for hypoxia-driven mortality by a median of 1.02±0.15% saturation°C-1 or 0.07±0.01mgO2L-1°C-1. The corresponding Q10 values averaged 3.01±0.29 for the median survival time and 2.09±0.20 for the median lethal oxygen concentration. Use of these Q10 values predicts that the 4°C warming expected during the 21st century will lead to survival times 35.6% lower under hypoxia and that the threshold oxygen concentrations for high mortality to occur will increase by, on average, 25.5% if bottom water temperature increased by 4°C. Hence, ocean warming is expected to increase the vulnerability of benthic macrofauna to reduced oxygen concentrations and expand the area of coastal ecosystems affected by hypoxia. © 2010 Blackwell Publishing Ltd.","Benthic community; Global warming; Hypoxia; Impacts; Oxygen","benthos; bottom water; global warming; hypoxia; oxygen; temperature effect",,,,,,"Altieri, A.H., Dead zones enhance key fisheries species by providing predation refuge (2008) Ecology, 89, pp. 2808-2818; Bakun, A., Global climate change and intensification of coastal ocean upwelling (1990) Science, 247, pp. 198-201; Bakun, A., Weeks, S.J., Greenhouse gas buildup, sardines, submarine eruptions and the possibility of abrupt degradation of intense marine upwelling ecosystems (2004) Ecology Letters, 7, pp. 1015-1023; Bladé, I., Cacho, I., Castro-Díez, Y., (2010) Clima en España: Pasado, presente y futuro. Informe de evaluación del cambio climático regional, , MICINN and MMAMRM, Madrid. Available at; Bograd, S.J., Castro, C.G., Di Lorenzo, E., Palacios, D.M., Bailey, H., Gilly, W., Chavez, F.P., Oxygen declines and the shoaling of the hypoxic boundary in the California Current (2008) Geophysical Research Letters, 35, pp. L12607. , doi: DOI: 10.1029/2008GL034185; Boleza, K.A., Burnett, L.E., Burnett, K.G., Hypercapnic hypoxia compromises bactericidal activity of fish anterior kidney cells against opportunistic environmental pathogens (2001) Fish & Shellfish Immunology, 11, pp. 593-610; Brooks, S.P.J., Dezwaan, A., Vandenthillart, G., Cattani, O., Cortesi, P., Storey, K.B., Differential survival of Venus gallina and Scapharca inaequivalvis during anoxic stress - covalent modification of phosphofructokinase and glycogen-phosphorylase during anoxia (1991) Journal of Comparative Physiology B-Biochemical Systemic and Environmental Physiology, 161, pp. 207-212; Brown, J.H., Gillooly, J.F., Allen, A.P., Savage, V.M., West, G.B., Toward a metabolic theory of ecology (2004) Ecology, 85, pp. 1771-1789; Cade, B.S., Noon, B.R., A gentle introduction to quantile regression for ecologists (2003) Frontiers in Ecology and the Enviro